Images: ["[2011-05-23T12...](https://chinese.aljazeera.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/2011-05-23T120000Z_975879172_BM2E75N159901_RTRMADP_3_GERMANY-1687250625-1687339129.jpg)", "[image-1687339...](https://chinese.aljazeera.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/image-1687339197.jpg)", "[image-1-16873...](https://chinese.aljazeera.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/image-1-1687339267.jpg)"]

Topics: ['新闻', '科技']

Keywords: ['新闻', '科技', '世界']

Type: Article

<!--METADATA-->

![](Images/Aljazeera Chinese/2023-06-21T10-00-46/2011-05-23T120000Z_975879172_BM2E75N159901_RTRMADP_3_GERMANY-1687250625-1687339129.jpg)Many laboratories around the world have published research on creating pre -printing versions similar to human embryonic structures in the past 7 days. Experts said they should be cautious because they have not been reviewed by colleagues.(Reuters)Scientists first used stem cells to create a structure similar to human embryo in the laboratory, which prompted people to call on scientists to implement stricter supervision of rapidly developing stem cell research.

In the past 7 days, many laboratories around the world have released a pre -print version of research reports to explain their research, and experts have said that they should treat such studies with caution and have not yet been reviewed by peer.

These laboratories use different technologies to encourage human embryonic stem cells (can be differentiated into any type of cells) to self -develop into a structure similar to embryo without sperm, eggs or fertilization.

The purpose of this study is to provide a model in line with ethics for scientists. Unprecedented ways to study human embryos, and hope to obtain new insights on birth defects, genetic diseases, infertility and other problems during pregnancy. Essence

The first announcement of this research was released on Wednesday (14th this month). At that time, the professor of Cambridge University and the California Institute of Technology Magda Lenica Zenica Gotz introduced the research by her team at the Annual Meeting of the International Stem Cell Studies Society in Boston.

The British "Guardian" first reported her related introduction.

Subsequently, the team of Jacob Hannah at the Institute of Science in the Institute of Science in Israel released a pre -printed version of the study on the 15th to introduce their research on human embryo models based on stem cells.

Zenica Gotz's team subsequently released their pre-print version research and provided more information. China and other laboratories in the United States have also followed suit and released different pre -printed version research later last week.

The researchers refuted the media reports called "synthetic embryos", and said that they were not synthesis in the strict sense, but grew from stem cells, and should not be regarded as embryo.

![](Images/Aljazeera Chinese/2023-06-21T10-00-46/image-1687339197.jpg)Edit Human Genome: Scientists meet to discuss rare diseases(news agency)#### "It's almost incredible"

A large amount of data highlights the high competitiveness of research in this field.

In August last year, Zenica Gotz's team and Jacob Hanna's team have published research papers on their first embryonic structures on their use of mice stem cells.

Both teams told AFP reporters that their latest research has been accepted by the famous peer review journals -and they have shown their work at academic conferences a few months before the recent media attention.

Hana refused to accept the views of both teams as "first" and claimed that they had achieved very different achievements.

He told AFP reporters that his model structure has the characteristics of "placenta, yolk, amniotic cavity" and other embryo characteristics, while Zenica Gotz's structure lacks such characteristics.

Other researchers also seemed to agree that Hanna's model was more advanced, and praised its team to induce cells into embryo -like structures by only chemical rather than genetically modified.

Jesse Vifrite, a researcher at the Institute of Biology and Genetics of Max Planck in Germany, said, "Henna's model has obvious similarity with natural embryos, which is almost incredible."

Grand River Vidella, a stem cell biology expert in Reading University in the United Kingdom, told AFP that it is best to wait for colleagues to review these studies.

But he added that "the impact of these two studies is huge."

"We should try to avoid unhealthy hype, because this technology is still in the early stages, but new guidelines have been needed."

![](Images/Aljazeera Chinese/2023-06-21T10-00-46/image-1-1687339267.jpg)Scientists have developed a robot that can deform from solid state to liquid state(Peninsula TV Station)
####  In the "Black Box Period"?

The two laboratories stated that the embryo model they developed reached 14 days, which is also the statutory period for many national laboratories to cultivate human embryos.

After 14 days, the embryo will begin to form different organs including the brain, and this period is also known as the "Black Box" because people know very little about embryo development at this stage.

Research regulations in this field vary from the country or region, but most of them are suitable for fertilized embryos, and new embryo models can be empty.

The University of Cambridge said on Friday that it had launched a project to develop the first stem cell management framework in the UK based on human embryo models.

Related scientists emphasized that they have no intention of implanted their embryo models into the human uterus -and even if they do so, they will not produce babies.

Vidella said that as a part of early research, the embryo model implanted with female macaques did induce some signs of pregnancy, but did not survive.

James Brisco, a Francis Crick Institute in Britain, called on researchers to act "cautious, careful, and transparently act.

He also emphasized that "the danger lies in mistakes or unreasonable claims, which will have a chilling effect on the public and policy makers, and this will be a major setback in the field."

